text: You could interchange any movie title here and it would just be a movie about a entrepreneur trying to make it big.Â   Nothing especially Jobs specific here, and once again it looks like Sorkin has gone for dramatic dialogue over historical integrity. None of the characters look like their real life counterparts, none of them act like their real life counterparts, and I'm sure when the full movie comes out, there will be gaps in the history too - all for the sake of some "smart" writing.  As much as Steve was an "asshole" in his day to day life, the story seems to be focusing way too much on that, and not on the journey he underwent to get there. Pirates of Silicon Valley managed to capture his swaying emotions whilst keeping the story about Apple and Microsoft and their quests to change the world.

text: I don't know why people keep using the "Ashton Kutcher looks more like Jobs!!!" defence when the Ashton Kutcher version of Jobs bombed at the box office AND got terrible reviews. Kutcher can't act. Clearly, looks aren't everything. Simply looking like someone else doesn't require talent. All Kutcher had going for him was that he resembled Jobs. He didn't grab the audience's attention. He just made people think, "Wow, he really looks like Jobs!" Michael Fassbender CAN act. He may not look like Jobs, but he's talented, and that's way more important in capturing the essence of a person. Fassbender can capture the mannerisms, the energy, the spirit of Jobs. On top of all that, this movie has an amazing cast, writer, and director. This trailer alone looks more interesting than any second of the 2013 movie.

text: Fun Fact about Steve Jobs. This is a FACT that very few people know, not even those involved in making this movie any other movie or likely those that have written about Steve. Â Maybe it's time to set the record straight.....Most of you know that Steve Jobs passed away while fighting cancer, but first a few things of note.....did he die because the cancer consumed him? Possibly, more likely it was because he had a liver transplant while he still had metastatic cancer in his body. Usually this is a big no no partly due to the fact that a liver transplant or any transplant requires immune suppressing anti-rejection drugs. If you have cancer cells active in your body there is very little to stop them after a transplant. But who knows for sure, but this is the most likely scenario based on the facts. What kind of cancer did he have....? Pancreatic, Liver ? NO, Steve Jobs was a PNet...a what? Pnet is an acronym for pancreatic neuroendocrine cancer....hmmm so he had pancreatic cancer then? NO not quite, he Â had neuroendocrine cancer with a primary tumor in his pancreas and metastasis to his liver and likely other locations too. This is a completely different kind of cancer than the pancreatic cancer that killed Patrick Swayze within a year or 2. Nets patients commonly live years and even decades continually battling tumors as they slowly spread through out their bodies. This is why Steve had at least ten years and perhaps could have lived longer with better treatment choices. He did one thing right when he went to Basal Switzerland for PRRT treatment.For most patients this stabilizes the disease for several years. It is not yet available in the USA Â except as a clinical trial here and there. So not yet FDA approved, however it is the gold standard of treatment for this disease in just about every country on the planet for the last 15 years or more. So here's the thing...many NETS patients (also known as Carcinoid cancer) suffer a complicated set of symptoms that are collectively known as Carcinoid syndrome. I won't go into all the details as they are different inmany patients. One of those set of symptoms is a little doosey that is known as CARCINOID RAGE ....GRrrr !!! Not often talked about in the community by patients or doctors probably due to associated stigma. It is a very Â specific set of psychotic symptoms that are best described by well, Steve Jobs could have been the ideal poster boy let's say. Everything you have noted (correctly) are due to the specific actions of certain hormones, peptides, serotonin being released upon the brain and body. Â Studies have shown marriages and relationships being broken, jobs lost, careers ruined among many other horrible outcomes. The average time to a correct diagnosis with this disease (after presenting with symptoms) is 7-10 YEARS ! Many people have had it for decades perhaps as far back as childhood undiagnosed. It's a slow slow cancer most of the time. Some studies have demonstrated that a diagnosis could be made years earlier based on the patients mental health. Â  In other words in case some of you have missed the point....Steve Jobs demonstrated the symptoms of his disease for many years and continued to get worse just as the disease got worse. Why do I know this? Because my wife has this disease. She was diagnosed over 4 years ago. However I'd say at least 7 or 8 years prior to that i noticed her behavior changing, her anger just totally absurd, off the wall tantrums for no reason blaming others for nothing in a fit of massive range. So bad was it that 2 years prior to her diagnosis I was researching online, printed some articles on carcinoid RAGE and cancer, filed it away and discovered those papers a year after her diagnosis....I had been on the right track just didn't realize at the time. So people now you know the true reason for Steve Jobs's outrageous behavior and why it was displayed and got worse for years. Could he have taken drugs for that to control it ? Â Maybe there's not much help in that area of the disease especially since it is rare, they are focusing on the disease itself rather than all the other aspects. However many patients take a long acting monthly shot of a synthetic hormone known as Octreotide or Sandostatin Lar. This helps control many of the disease symptoms especially the physical such as facial/chest flushing, severe diarrhea, heart disease and to some extent the 'noid rages as we call them. There is a lot to this little known but most virulent of all cancers it strikes many and in many parts of the body and lays hidden confounding doctors for many years. Â So every body cut Steve a little slack, in a sense he was mentally ill (stigma) but yet still changed all of our worlds forever. I for one am grateful, even though I am a die-hard Android fan ! Â This is likely the first time that what I have revealed regarding Steve Jobs is now publicly available. To Steve's family....I apologize, Â but the world has a right to know and there are many others suffering whom might benefit from greater awareness of this disease and its effects. I think honestly Steve would agree.

text: I am absolutely, positively impressed by the look of this movie. Regardless of all of the drama and behind the scenes work it took to get this movie green lit. I think that it is coming across nicely.  Sure, wouldn't I would love to see this film done by Fincher and led by Bale would have been absolutely perfect as Jobs? Sure I would, but I must say seeing this in the hands of someone like Danny Boyle and being led by Michael Fassbender is going to be a true win/win. What was Fincher and Bale's loss will be Boyle and Fassbender's gain.  I think that more and more Michael Fassbender is becoming a true A-lister leading man in everything that he does. He is getting better and better. He is going to totally crush this movie. I would not be surprised if he carries this movie all the way to Oscar season and to get it nominated. He is a very intelligent and versatile actor and he may not look like Jobs but he is like clay in the hands of Boyle and he has allowed himself to be molded into him.  But I am also impressed with the supporting cast around him. From Seth Rogan, to Jeff Daniels, to what I think is an almost invisibly and totally invested into her role, Kate Winslet who has gotten so much better the older she gets much like Tom Hanks has evolved. I can see her easily get another Oscar on her mantle.  Overall, I could see this film become what Birdman did last year. I think that as Danny Boyle has brought an energy and life to this film I think that he also brings a sense and has made it almost made this movie feel visceral and tangibly alive before our very eyes.  We shall see whenever this movie comes out later this year if it is what this trailer says it is.

text: Apple and Steve Jobs didn't steal the interface. Yes, they visited Xerox Palo Alto Research Park and saw the graphical user interface there. They gave Xerox shares of Apple for the use of it. Xerox saw no commercial value in it. Apple then fixed it cleaned it up and made it into a usable commercial product - the Mac OS. Also technically speaking Woz also wasn't an engineer. He had no engineering degree and had no professional license as an "engineer." He was also wasn't a scientist with any tru schooling in science. He was a self-taught, technical tinkerer who intuitively knew how to invent a product from his intuitive science and engineering skills and understanding. I guess that makes him an engineer and a scientist BUT Steve Jobs also knew how to engineer a product from an invention and now to engineer a company from those products so to say Woz was an engineer and/or scientist and not say Jobs had similar skills is a little off the mark. However, what Woz failed to realize is his inventions and his skills were not recognized without Steve Jobs' ability to put in all into the proper perspective and packaging - a product people will buy and most importantly use.

text: My pet rock died in my arms last night. He lived a long, and good life. Come bath time, he would like to run and hide under the bed. The back window of the car was his favorite place to ride. text: Oh. My. Lord. I'm so sick of the "he doesn't look like Steve Jobs so he's going to be terrible" comments. Keep in mind, Michael Fassbender might be one of the greatest actors working right now in full honesty, and people are actually DEFENDING Ashton Kutcher, who turned in a cheesy-at-best performance whose only redeeming quality was that he LOOKED like Steve Jobs. It shouldn't matter if Fassbender looks like Jobs; as long as he can embody who he was and turn in a compelling performance that suits the story, there's no reason to criticize him.  Also, when did it matter whether or not the actor looked like who they were playing? Look at a movie like "I'm Not There," where they got 6 different actors (including a woman) to play embodiments of Bob Dylan. Or even recently with "Love and Mercy," neither Paul Dano nor John Cusack look at all like Brian Wilson. However, in both cases, those movies were fantastic and all the actors were compelling and did a terrific job regardless, because they at least captured the soul of who those people were, and suspended the disbelief.  In conclusion, anybody can look like someone else, it takes true talent to embody the essence of someone else.

text: Jobs saw great stuff and knew it was the future before the future did, orchestrating the work of hackers and tinkerers into something resembling a consumer product. He parlayed the profits and success of the Apple ][ into the next revolutionary products, including laser printers and the first computers with graphical user interfaces. When Apple was flagging, Jobs was able to return and restructure Apple into a fount of innovation based directly on technologies he fostered through NeXT after leaving Apple, themselves based on other technologies, such as OOP, that impressed him on his visits to Xerox-PARC. He shepherded the company and a huge community of users and developers through a transition from 680x0 processors running Pascal, C, and C++ to G3/G4/G5 processors with a whole new Unix-based OS based on a weird C dialect, and finally to Intel and ARM processors running Swift, keeping apps like Photoshop and MS Office running on Macs throughout. In his final act he introduced high-quality mobile computing to the masses and set the direction for Apple's next 30 years. When someone devotes so much of his life to being a leader and a visionary, it does not surprise me that he often falls short in ordinary human relationships.

text: Why are people so passionate about dissing Jobs? I mean I get there's a "holier than thou" attitude in some fans, but he was a very interesting and productive man, you can't deny that, but the whole "he didn't invent anything" camp is just absurd, he wasn't an inventor, he was a great entrepreneur, team leader, business man and visionary, he doesn't need to also be an engineer to be someone worthy of recognition for the work he did.  He was a very important agent of change for the industry and there's no denying that.  Was he a dick and some of his business practices unfair? of course, but that's a consequence of him being a flawed human being like everyone else.

text: Much like the casting of Jesse Eisenberg in The Social Network this film (despite having Boyle in the drivers seat instead of Fincher) is looking for someone to capture the spirit of Aaron Sorkin's written depiction of the character. Much like Eisenberg looked and sounded nothing like Mark Zuckerberg he projected Zuckerberg's egotistical dominant persona that was perfect for the film. Here it seems Fassbender is reflecting Jobs' voice, mannerisms but most of all Sorkin's evident depiction of a character believing himself to be superior to others. Ironically similar to Zuckerberg. It's not about straight imitation when giving a performance but dissection making a character's motivation visible to the audience.

text: Why do we need another one of these? Ash Kutcher did SJ pretty decent justice. This actually looks / feels worse, but it's just a trailer.  I don't even like the guy. He made a huge mess of the video industry and then closed the doors for every fan boy to gloat from behind. Sure, he had an assload of talent but it was more a talent of punching his employees in the face with a ten ton invisible hammer, interface design and marketing like the British when they took over the world with their unrivaled superiority complexes and muskets.  Doesn't mean he made or his legacy continues to make superior products at a reasonable cost. Some aspects were superior for their time and heinously expensive for what they were but in the world of electronics, that time is very, very short.   The only thing I really respect that he did was save Pixar and find the right people to make it great. That was a huge risk and the world is better for it. Apple...  if they just went the way of Linux, I'd have a warmer heart. They'd be nothing without the iPod. That one thing and music piracy is what _made_ Apple what it is. The rest is just frills and mediocre, confusing software just like Microsoft.

Apple tried to control the market and still does.  They are one of the most power hungry companies out there that almost went bankrupt a few times because of it.  They don't learn their lesson. text: I worked for Apple. It bothers me that Fassbender looks nothing like Jobs. I know that it probably shouldn't matter as long as he gives a good performance, but the fact that the looks are off completely distracts me from the story. Can't help it - it's just my natural response. The other thing that bothers me is the futuristic techno artistic direction. On the one hand, it's kind of unique and cool, but it's also not quite Apple. Guess realism wasn't a priority for the filmmakers and they're going for something more abstract. My favorite Jobs film is still "Pirates of Silicon Valley".

text: I grew up in Silicon Valley. My brother was friends with Steve Job's daughter, (they used to party and hang out). I could tell you stories about the poor girl and the family that Jobs ignored in his ambition to build the next best tech. toy. The angle that I viewed his life from was a sad tale of obsession, but I knew he was a creative powerhouse and innovator as well. I'm interested to see the film and I cannot think of a better actor to play Jobs than Fassbender. He plays broken, but dynamic men like he was born into the roles.

text: You always read and see how Jobs was an a-hole to his staff but stories about Microsoft in those days paint Bill Gates as a much bigger a-hole, shouting and ranting at them, paying very little, demanding they work inhuman hours, treating women (how few there were) in the company like shit, pushing everyone to their breaking point. How come no one has made that movie yet? Oh, because he is still alive and almost seems to enjoy litigation where he can show off how smart he is. And yes, I saw Pirates of Silicon Valley, but that movie barely scratches how obsessed  Gates was in those days. Read "Hard Drive" to get the mostly true story of Microsoft..
author: cbstevp

text: I just watched the movie.  Mediocre at best.  More of the same.  If you read that book about Steve Jobs (I forgot the author's name) you already knew that Jobs was a genius and an asshole.  The asshole part was very very obvious from this Documentary.  It's more of a statement about US than him.   Why do WE idolize assholes?  Yes Jobs made amazing products but stillâ€¦..he was dishonest (criminally at times), arrogant, treated most people like shit, was a bully and had very little empathy for people.    But here's the thing.  ALL geniuses have certain things in common.  They have vision, creativity, charisma and are goal-driven.  They are perfectionists.  Really they are all so similar.  This all reminds me of Michael Jackson.  He had all the same qualities except he was NOT an asshole.  Actually the opposite.  I don't think there has ever been a genius who was also an amazingly kind, caring and humble human being.  And a great humanitarian.  My question is why aren't we celebrating him?  And why wasn't his name included in this Jobs Documentary with other "geniuses" and iconic people?  Lennon's name was in there.  Lady Diana's name was in there.  Michael Jackson changed the world of music forever and brought enormous joy to millions of people the world over.  He spent his life giving back (in terms of time and money) to help the less fortunate of the world.  He was the most famous man in the world and there will NEVER be another Michael Jackson.  So what are we doing?  Idolize an asshole like Steve Jobs and ignore a wonderful human being like Michael Jackson?  What is wrong with us?

text: Watched this movie. I loved everybody's performances except maybe Seth Rogen's. Michael Fassbender may not look the part but man what an amazing performance, probably the current front runner for best actor Oscar. I loved the electric direction, amazing cinematography and snappy dialogue. My gripe with the film though, is the structure. It being held during three product launches, while unique, strained a lot of believability for me in terms of the character interactions and developments. So while it was creative take on Steve's life I also feel it was to the films detriment. I still liked it though, I thought it was good. I'd give it a 7/10.

text: MY RATING - 6 out of 10.  I love watching Screen writer , Aaron Sorkin's work. The West Wing and The NewsroomÂ  are two of my favourite TV shows of all time and all I can say than god Sorkin was involved with this film because otherwise it could have been a disaster. This is not a biography of Steve Jobs more a character assassination of the man.  It revolves around four product launches and the arguments he has at the time with nearly everyone around him.  It feels like a redemption movie but Steve Jobs wasn't that bad as to make the point. He was a businessman and acted like most successful driven people do.  The stand out performance is from Seth Rogan ( you won't here me say that too often!) who plays Steve Wozniak . I only wish Rogan would play straight roles more often, Overall this is watchable for the fast flowing , Sorkin Dialogue , but other than that , because of the strange format , it's quite forgettable.

text: Apple products are gimmicky and unnecessary. But their software is really good. If I were to hold both an android on one hand and an iphone on the other, I'd admire the iphone more, how it feels on my hand and fingers, and how smoothly it functions. The screen for the iphone is made of real glass (making it so much easier to crack) whereas the android feels like you're tapping on a plastic screen. There is not much freedom to downloading content and is a headache having to keep syncing with the iphone. On the other hand, you get so much more out of an android phone. You can download a variety of formats straight off the browser and simply plug to a PC, drag and drop between folders.  Android: Actually a smart phone.  iPhone: Feels nice, looks nice.

text: To people who complain about apple products being so expensive, coming from a neutral neutral point of view between Apple and Android products etc etc. They both are extremely expensive. Yeah you might be able to say there are really "cheap" android phones compared to the cheapest iphone, say a mid-range android device goes for 200$ to give an example. It might be a great phone, have great internals and good quality build, for much less than an iphone. But... Do you have any idea how much it costs  to make that 200$ phone? How much some chinese worker is paid to assemble it? 10$ it costs to make it in massive production. 190$ profit for example from the phone creator, be it Apple or Android. That's how capitalism works, you think you get a good deal, that's what sellers are trying to make you believe, you are all getting ripped off, its part of capitalism, the trick is to make people not notice it, to make you believe you get a good deal, be it whatever phone you are buying, you are not getting a good deal, you are probably paying 10x what is cost to make. This is not true for phones, but just about anything really.

text: I think this movie is about how you can feel  one way about a computer, or a car, or a work  of art, and quite another way, concerning the  person who made it.  The creator and his creation  are not the same, are they?  And neither should  the message be confused with the messenger,   because he did not author that message, did he?   "You're the only one in the world who cares that  it should be housed in a perfect cube".  Yet, in the  person of Jesus Christ, it could be said that the  Messenger IS the Message, for He is the Word  made flesh.  And his Father, the Author.  Today, I  was at a grocery store, paying for a carton of eggs  and some cream, and as the cashier handed me the  change, some coin fell out of my hand and rolled into   a "help feed hungry children" donation box.  And I  thought upon how different actions are from intent.   Jesus said that He always does His Father's Will.   Yet, in the Garden of Gethsemene, he prayed, while  his sweat fell from his head as great drops of blood,  and he prayed : "May this cup of suffering pass from  me, but not MY WILL, Father, but yours be done."   Personally, I do not trust charitable organizations  and they who run them.  Yet, I made, it would seem,  a donation today.  "He means what he says, and he  says what he means".  Know anybody, that honest?   Such that others do not ask, What did he mean?   But, what does THAT mean?  The world?     "Eh little buddy.."  Sarcasm?  For Steve W. looks like  he's got a free pass at Burger King.  .. A fruitarian who  did not shower.. Difficult to tell who is who, is it not?   The iPod Sermon :  What seed is planted?  What choices  made?  What incubates therein?  Touch, but take care  what you choose to accept.

When actors speak Sorkinese they seem so coherent and heaps intelligent. Fassbender is my fav. It's coincidence that Jobs named the cube 'Next' and Gen Next (after X) would be the first Gen to grow up using its OS - a Mac that looked like 'Judy Jestson's  bake oven, for 'a Generation that would be the first to have the advantages of Jetson like technology'. Almost as freakish as Jobs meeting Arthur C Clark as a young boy; freakish that it is documented footage.  Although baby Jobs doesnâ€™t look all that  interested as Clark (with weird exactitude) talks about a future the young boy will orchestrate into being. Not so freakish that Clark (a futurist) would hold such a vision of the future after all his imagination gave birth to Hal -an artificial intelligent PA with a natural language interphase. text: Oh my Lord. STOP COMPLAINING ABOUT THIS FILM. THAT'S WHAT IT IS. A FILM. it is not a big fanboy made film for Apple nerds to geek out about to sell a new iPhone or to boost Steve Jobs' legacy to an 11.  You want to know the reason why this film was made? Probably because Jobs (2013) was a critical and commercial failure and I'd much rather see that film get remade and get proper filmmaking behind it or we could get endless Friday the 13th reboots. You can say he looks nothing like Steve Jobs. Fair. But do you want Ashton Kutcher to play Jobs, get hired because he looks like him, thank you makeup, and get a nomination at the Razzies or Fassbender get hired because of his acting ablilities and get a nomination at the Oscars?   Matt Whitely. Do you know who Matt Whitely is? Of course you don't. He only has one credit on IMDb and that's for writing Jobs. They took someone who had no experience in anything. No commercials, short films, not even writing anything. When I first searched up Matt Whitely on Yahoo Search, the first answer I got were profiles on Facebook. If I look up Danny Boyle or Aaron Sorkin, at least I get a sidebar to the right showing their pictures and occupations. That's who we got. Now would you rather have them or someone who could have been cleaning up popcorn off theater floors for all we know?  They didn't make this film for a cash grab. They had it in production before the 2013 film came out or was even in production. Now it's getting hate because apparently it didn't come out fast enough to compete with the first one. It was made because we wanted a well made film of this and we got one.  I could ramble forever about Steve jobs himself and the backlash against him and his character. It doesn't paint him as a man who has done nothing wrong. It paints him as a man who did put quality before other people in his life and himself and it did it with grace and dignity. It knows what to say and that's the fact that no one knew how to feel about him, his morals, his ethics. It shows you and lets you decide.  I'm tired of everyone judging this film for things it never did.

text: Although many viewers will have hoped for a success story of how Steve Jobs created Apple in his garage, they are instead confronted with a darker look into the life of Steve Jobs and the obstacles he faced. This movie may not be as slick and cool as the social network, however it still remains an excellent biopic.   The key reason why this film wasn't a box office success lies in mixed critic reception. A film of this genre has to gain impeccable reviews to fill cinema seats.  However I believe this film was snubbed and deserved both acclaim and box office success.   This is not one to be missed.
